There are many cat fountains on the market which create constant movement of the water. Some time ago I took PETSAFE DRINKWELL ORIGINAL DRINKING FOUNTAIN:

https://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/PETSAFE-DRINKWELL-ORIGINAL-DRINKING-FOUNTAIN-FILTERS-AERATES-WATER-DOG-CAT/132112805830?hash=item1ec2896fc6:g:NXEAAOSwTM5Yt~mZ

It's working well but even if it has carbon filter it requires weekly cleaning (the walls cover with geesy substrate from bacteria) and filter replacement.

From other side I noticed that the cat prefers to drink the water directly from the tap. That's why I designed this fountain for tap water and it was really well appreciated from my cat.

The idea behind the tap fountain is quite simple - a holder for the tap nose (with small draft to tight to the tap pipe) and a small shallow pool from where the cat drinks the water. The excessive water is coming out from wide and curved channel in beautiful way, the water is fresh and cold (the tap water in our city has excellent quality).

I plan to make a second design with even smoother shapes and with more universal tap holder (at the moment the design was made especially for my Grohe tap with 23.2mm diameter end).

Some live video how it works:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KGwsbl4mqOk

title: Antenna Mount | FPV Antenna | Receiver Antenna | Martian 2

description.text: After modifying my Martian 2 to a lowrider, I needed a good way to mount my FPV and RX antennas. I like to make my builds look clean and zipties just wouldn't cut it for this build, so I made this TPU mount. Its got a hole that you can screw your VTX pigtail into, or you can just push the antenna through there. I also added 2 small holes for the RX antennas. One hole is parallel to the ground, and the other is at about a 45 degree angle. This should serve as a guide for your antennas to get optimal signal. Ideally, you would want them to be at 90 degrees from each other, so after you've run the antenna with heatshrink through the holes, just bend the top one up. This mount is only 20mm tall and 32mm wide, since it is meant for my low rider, but the mount will slide over any standard 5mm standoffs.

title: Taz 7 style hybrid bed belt clamp for a Taz 6

description.text:
The Taz 6 belt clamp is weaker than the one the Taz 5 and previous had, and has been a source of issues for the otherwise generally more robust taz 6. The new Taz 7 beta parts look better, but they changed the geometry on them so they don't line up with the stock taz 6 mount spots. This project combines the Taz 6 and Taz 7 styles, taking the better elements from both, and combines them into a taz 6 form factor. I then also made a version 2 that adds 2 more heat set inserts and splits the belt mounts for easier adjusting of one side of the belt.

You will also need 4 M5 heat set inserts (or 2 for version 1) 4 M2 heat set inserts, the stock limit switch bolts and switches, the stock bed bolts, 2 or 4 M3 botls and washers, probably 8mm for the bolts? to hold the belt down. The path is a bit different than the stock 6, so be prepared to fit a slightly longer belt if needed. The overall geometry should be the same though.

Let me know if it needs any changes!

Edit 1: Apparently there is an already existing stock lulzbot upgrade similar to this I didn't see. it's available here if you want a more factory supported variant: https://devel.lulzbot.com/TAZ/Olive/production_parts/printed_parts/y_belt_mount/

description.text:
Update Make sure you give your astrobox/raspberrypi a static ip, because if the ip changes this will have to be redone (at least the keygen part).

Hey everyone! GoldenGears here, I wanted to share with you something I was able to throw together. I kept seeing people setting their simplify3D processes to auto upload to octoprint using cURL and I wanted to be able to do the same with Astroprint. Below is my step by step directions (written for mac but can be adapted for other platforms) on how to achieve this. If you have any questions or ways you think it could be improved let me know. eventually I would like it to auto upload and print but I haven;t quite figured out how to remotely tell the astrobox to print. Anyways here you go!

First open up terminal

enter: ssh [email protected]_pi_ip
(replace "your_pi_ip" with the ip address of your AstroBox)

Enter the password for your raspberry pi (Default password: raspberry)

enter: sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config

Find the line that starts with "PermitRootLogin"

change the line to "PermitRootLogin yes"

hit control-O and hit enter to save the file

hit control-X to exit the nano editor

enter: sudo /etc/init.d/ssh restart

wait for the process to finish and return to your normal prompt for commands

enter: sudo passwd root
(this will allow you to change the root user password)

Enter your new desired root password and hit enter

re-enter your new password and hit enter one more time

exit the terminal

start new terminal session

enter: ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 2048

enter: ssh-copy-id root:your_pi_ip
(replace "your_pi_ip" with the ip address of your AstroBox)

Enter the new root password you just created and hit enter

Wait for success (when it returns back to normal command prompt) and then close terminal

Open simplify3d

Under your process go to scripts and in the post processing box enter:
scp [output_filepath] [email protected]_pi_ip:../../AstroBoxFiles/uploads
(replace "your_pi_ip" with the ip address of your AstroBox)

And thats it, from now on when you click save Toolpaths to Disk on the preview page and save it to whatever location of your choice it’ll upload it to your AstroBox automatically.

Hope that adds some convenience to your printing! Enjoy!

I needed a set of visocity meters and found drawings with rough dimensions online for different types. This collection is for ISO 9431 standard cups in dimensions 3, 4, 6 and 8 mm.

The "ISO mm.stl" files are full cups with correct hole size. The "ISO cup basis.stl" in combination with the " mm tip.stl" files form a complet set of cup with inserts for reduced filament use.

The four different dimensions cover these ranges of viscosity:
3 mm: 4.6-52 cSt
4 mm: 19-163 cSt
6 mm: 84-823 cSt
8 mm: 187-2711 cSt

The formulas for calculating viscosity from the flow time are:
3 mm: V=0.443t-200/t
4 mm: V=1.37t-200/t
6 mm: V=6.90t-570/t
8 mm: V=21.78t-306/t

Where V is kinematic viscosity in cSt (centiStokes) and t is time for cup to empty in seconds.

Please note that you cannot trust the values as these are plastic replicas and true viscosity cups are precision machined from aluminium and stainless steel. It is possible to test the accuracy by using calibration fluids specified in the standard.

comments.text: It's regular white PLA spray painted gold using MTN 94 "Frame Gold" color. A can of high end art Spray Paint is usually a lot cheaper than a roll of even generic PLA, so it is easier to have more colours on hand. The grooves created by each layer form a great surface for the paint to attach to, and the matte nature of the paint reduces that particularly weird reflectiveness of most PLA prints in darker colours that 3D printer owners tend to love/hate. Spray paint also allows you to introduce multiple colours in to prints or even create really beautiful gradients, and allows for much more subtle colors - seeing as most filament providers, especially the cheap ones, seem addicted to bright neon colors.

title: RF30 X-Axis Endstop Toggle Switch Mount

description.text:
This is a little mount / cover to use a single 3-way toggle switch as a min/max endstop along with the pre-existing sliding bumpers on the Rong Fu RF-30 mill drill. I couldn't find a NC 3-way toggle switch, so I'm running a traditionally-less-failsafe NO circuit. I figured it's a toss-up since the likelihood of metal chips getting into the housing for a NC rig and shorting it to fail closed is about the same as anything coming apart in the NO circuit and failing it open.

Either way, make sure you have an emergency kill that works and only use your endstops while you're actively paying attention to the machine.

title: Using a Cheap Tire Gauge as a Probe

description.text:
Update 20-FEB-2018:
I made a SMD PCB. See picture. This is my first attempt at getting a board made. I used PCBWay in China. The board differs from the original schematic. It uses a 1.5V LDO regulator to supply power to the caliper, and a different MOSFET. If anyone is interested in the Gerber files or you would like a board and/or parts (at cost, continental US only), let me know via a message (I won't respond to comments regarding the PCB)

End of update.

https://youtu.be/TE63B3ymtIA

This is an implementation example of turning a cheap tire gauge into a digital probe. I designed this to read the cut depths of ordinary brass house keys for a key duplicating machine project I’m working on.

Probe Carriage:
The gauge is mounted to two 4mm x 97mm shafts. It moves along the shafts powered by a cheap BYJ48 stepper. The stepper is part of a simple rack and pinion. At one end there is an endstop used to detect when the probe is fully extended.

All of the parts except for the spring clip are printed with a 0.2mm layer height, 80% fill.
The spring clip is printed with a 0.1mm layer height, 100% fill.
All parts are printed without support.

Once the carriage is printed, the three holes to accept the LM4UU 4x8x12mm linear bearings need to be reamed to 8mm. Because it’s critical that the bearings are parallel and square to the base, I performed this task using a drill press. The carriage was mounted to a square block of wood with double stick tape to hold it square and parallel while reaming.

The carriage is attached to the depth gauge by removing the existing depth gauge back panel screws and replacing them with longer screws. The screws I used are pan head M2x15mm. I had to grind them down to 13mm.

The endstop/Mini Micro Switch is attached using 2 flathead M2.3 x 12mm screws (M2 will work fine too). You should add a chamfer to the switch holes so that the screw heads are flush with the switch body.
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Free-shipping-10PCS-2pin-N-O-N-C-5A250VAC-Limit-Switch-WK11-3Z-Mini-Micro-Switch/32273563395.html

The internal spring that keeps the probe extended is a 8.5 x 36.5mm extension spring. I have a few depth gauges that all look the same but the profile of the stem that the spring clip attaches to varies. I only made a clip that fits one of these profiles. I can give you the Fusion 360 file if you need to customize it for your depth gauge.

Software:
The interface for the caliper/tire depth gauge is an I2C version of the interface I published for the caliper plug ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2477494 )
The new interface uses an ATtiny85 acting as an I2C slave. The interface will notify the host whenever the caliper reading changes. See the schematic CaliperDataTiny85.pdf. One of the added features is the ability to zero the caliper from the I2C master. This is done by turning the caliper off then on. In order for this to work the caliper battery should be removed and 1.5V should be provided by the interface. The power is controlled by a 2N7000 MOSFET.

One of the tricky issues with using all 6 IO pins on the ATtiny85 is that you need to set the H fuse to 0x5F (otherwise pin PB5 is the RESET pin). I did this using an easy to build AVR high voltage programmer. See the included Software.zip. The file sketch AVR_HighVoltageSerialProgrammer.ino has a link to a page that describes how to build one. This sketch also contains the fuse settings for this project.

Classes Caliper and BYJ48: The Caliper class deals with all of I2C communication with the ATtiny85. The BYJ48 class controls the carriage stepper.

ProbeTest.ino demos the Caliper and BYJ48 classes.
CaliperI2CTest.ino is a subset of ProbeTest.ino that only demos the Caliper class.

I have been working on a project using this exact depth gauge, and was wondering about the data connector and whether or not I was smart enough to figure it out. Now we’ll never know, because you’ve done all the hard work! Thank you.

Unit fractions (1/N, for an natural number N) are interesting ideas in mathematics, dating all the way back to the ancient Egyptians. There are numerous ways to write a rational number as the sum of unit fractions. This is an an entry-level design project, allowing students to use their designs to play with basic ideas behind fractions. Among the files, 1 = 1/2 + 1/3 + 1/6, 1= 1/2 + 1/4 + 1/6 + 1/12, (1 = 1/2 + 1/3 + 1/10 + 1/15), (1 = 1/2 + 1/4 + 1/10 + 1/12 + 1/15), and 1 = 1/3 + 1/4 + 1/6 + 1/10 + 1/12 + 1/15. Of course, there are other ways to explore these ideas such as fraction bars and even 3D models (see Liu Hui's cube dissection).

description.text:
This is my first attempt at using Onshape so be gentle. Actually, any and all criticism is welcomed so that I can improve. The first design seemed a little 'clunky; to me so I redid it from the ground up.

Basic idea is that the top section is to hold a cigarette roller, the middle for papers/filters and the bottom for the tobacco. The roller's a pretty snug fit, hence no base in v02.

UPDATE
Well, it turns out that not all tins are created equal and v02 was having difficulty in fitting in to some due to the corner radius being too small. Hence v03 and v04 came along. They are also only 24.50mm high instead of 25.00mm as some tins have a raised section in the base.

v03 is for those who don't mind their papers/filters in with the tobacco (or just want more room) wile v04 still has the three compartments. Oh yeah, also rounded out the base corners in the tobacco compartment to make it easier to get the dust out.

Further Update -06 Nov 17
Working on an OpenSCAD version of this so will hopefully have a customizable Thing up soon.
Any suggestions/requests gratefully appreciated.

**Still working on the customizable version but if anyone wants an insert designed to their specs, drop me a line & I'll do what I can :-)

30 Dec 17
Finally got around to putting the thumb cutouts in and it makes a huge difference. I haven't uploaded v06 as I got the dimensions a little wrong in that one but v07 seems to be a nice all-round fit. There is only one compartment as, over time, the central divider just started annoying me (hard to get tobacco out etc).
Dimensions for this are 106 mm x 77 mm x 24 mm. Depending on the inner dimensions of your tin, just scale it in your slicer to fit
(desired dimension - model dimension) x 100 = scale.%

remixed_from.title: Wall box for battery operated sensor.

description.text: This is an offshoot of a wall mounted box design that I made for temperature and humidity sensors around the house. I decided to put some motion sensors around my house, so I needed a case design. With some modifications to the temperature and humidity sensor, the design was perfect.

Printer:

Anet A8

Notes:

Do not print this with supports. They are just too hard to remove. There will be a small bit of stringing under the tabs, but it is not noticeable as it is inside the case..

The motion sensor for this project is based on MySensors and can be found here: https://www.mysensors.org/build/motion.

The project is built on an easy newbie PCB designed by @sundberg84. The information on the board can be found here.

The battery pack that this is designed to work with is this style:

You will need to solder an extra wire to the battery pack to tap into the middle of the battery chain. This is done to get a 3 volt power leg that will power the arduino pro mini and nRF24L01 radio modules.

The motion sensor used for this is a modified HC-SR501 motion sensor

The image above is an unmodified version. The modification requires removing the 3.3v regulator and the input diode and soldering in a jumper to bypass the regulator circuit. This modification then allows you to run at the input voltage range specified by the BISS0001 chip which is 3v to 5v. The removal of the regulator and diode make the module more efficient for running on batteries. Here is a picture of a modified sensor.

The design of the wall box is a remix of my vented temperature and humidity sensor wall box. I did this mainly so that it would match the look of other wall mounted sensors in my house. The wall plate and box simply snap together for easy maintenance and battery replacement. The slot in the back is designed to fit the battery pack perfectly. The short posts next to the large hole in the front of the case are for mounting the HC-SR501 motion sensor module. It should be mounted using self tapping M2x5 to M2x8 screws. The PCB should be mounted using the same type of screws.
Thanks for checking out my design. Check out my website, https://dan.bemowski.info/ to see other things I have done related to 3D printing, electronics and home automation.

title: Sine Thread, fast printable thread library.

description.text:
OpenSCAD libraries for threads are slow.  Really slow.  Like 15-minutes-on-a-good-machine slow if you want more than a few threads on a screw.  But, if you are willing to approximate standard threads with a sine wave, you can use the 2d functions and extrude them fairly quickly.  A couple minutes can get you a ridiculously smooth thread that works with standard metric fasteners.  If you are OK with lowering the resolution it can be seconds.  
This is a script library, so it might not make a ton of sense to the uninitiated, but if you go over the code, all will be revealed.  
Obviously, the finer the layer height of the print, the closer to reality you get.  Depending on your machine and the resolution of your print, you may have to play with the scaling factor.  With a 0.1 layer height on a cheap Printrbot Simple, I got amazing threads that were just a bit tight on standard M4 fasteners without altering scale, but at lower resolutions, I needed to alter it slightly.  
This has lookup tables swiped from the ISOThread.scad library by Trevor Moseley.  Thanks Trevor.  If your library is on thingiverse, let me know and I'll set the remix thingie.  
I plan to expand this with more screw heads and such.

description.text: A small part used together with a nut and bolt to get an adjustable spring tension on the stock Rigidbot extruder.

Take apart the extruder and start by drilling a small (ca 1 mm) guide hole in the center of the cross holding the spring all the way through the lever.
Widen the hole to 3 mm all the way through.
Remove the remains of the cross with a sharp knife.
Drill the hole HALF WAY through to 4mm from the bottom (same side as where the cross were)
Mount a socket head screw, a nut, the printed part and the spring as shown in the pictures.
Reassemble the extruder and adjust the tension by turning the screw with a hex key through the hole :-)

description.text:
This is kind of a remix of a remix. It's a bit of a hybrid between the designs of lokster and Arjjck. It features the same semi circular design and mounting method from lokster's but retains the clean topology from Arjjck's. Lokster's was creating inconsistent layers when sliced (as seen in second photo).

I also added a structural element at the neck to keep it from bowing down if you print it with PLA. The semi circular design kind of fixes that too but I added it just for good measure.

The actual ring has been lowered a bit from lokster's design as well. The ring was a little too high for my preferences.

This isn't to say the the other two designs are wrong or bad in anyway. I just wanted to make one that fit my needs better and I thought maybe it would work better for other people too.

As you can see from the photos you'll have to remove the casing of the webcam and get to the bare electronics. This can be tricky for the inexperienced. There is a wire soldered to the board that has to be un-soldered and re-soldered. If you break your webcam it's not my fault, obviously.

Important note: There is a dab of glue on the side of the main lens that holds it at a certain focus distance. You'll have to remove that dab of glue with a small pick of some kind. After that you can screw the main lens in and out to change the focus distance. Here is a video showing that.

Here is my version of Portable power bank phone charger. I wanted high capacity and portability. I couldn’t find any others on Thingiverse when I started, so I made my own. After working on this for 3 months (Having to stop due to other projects) I saw one posted here. – Wow, Great minds think alike! Mine is not any better – just different implementation.
And while you may want one, it would be cheaper now to get the case and module in the kit offered by Banggood.com. DIY Kit Dual USB 5V 1A 2A Power Bank 18650 Battery Charger Box ;
https://www.banggood.com/DIY-Kit-Dual-USB-5V-1A-2A-Power-Bank-18650-Battery-Charger-Box-p-939385.html?rmmds=detail-top-buytogether

But that is not why you are on this site – you probably like the total DIY route!
So here are some the parts I used;

  1. Dual USB 5V 1A 2.1A Mobile Power Bank 18650 Battery Charger PCB Module Board
    https://www.banggood.com/Dual-USB-5V-1A-2_1A-Mobile-Power-Bank-18650-Battery-Charger-PCB-Module-Board-p-1031593.html?rmmds=detail-top-buytogether-auto.
  2. 18650 Batteries. Uitra Fire 3800mah without solder tabs Available just about everywhere. I constructed a battery powered spot welder to attach the soldering tabs.

Post Printing: Some trimming and sanding was necessary for the case to fit easily. Parts had to be installed before I found some of the fitting problems.
I blacked the inside of the led holder so the light would only go out the side. (Acrylic paint)

Case was ‘super glues’ together in the end. Just a couple of drops here and there.

Hope this project gives you inspiration to try something ‘new’. And of course, if you print one, please share your print on this site.

I used Fusion360 for designing this. This is the first project box I created that had to fit purchased components. I even ‘modeled’ the Charger Board in Fusion360 to help make the case fit. This lead to some problems. Like I didn’t model the solder connections – so my case has to be trimmed slighty for the ‘solder blobs’. Makes me appreciate the engineers who do this for a living!

Features:

  1. I incorporated channels for wiring and solder tabs.
  2. Four battery for extra capacity.
  3. Pins printed for the charger board to hold it in. Can be removed and maybe just melt some filament thru the hole for holding if needed. (wasn't needed for me)

I would suggest that you print the Led ‘lens’ out of clear filament or leave it out. I didn’t realize that this was a flashlight led rather than an indicator light. (the problem of getting boards from China with no instructions). A double push on the button turns the light on.

I printed this in PLA but the next one will be in ABS or PETG for temperature resistance. (like leaving in a car during the hot summer)

Build at your own risk. These batteries have been know to catch on fire. Suggestion would be to put pico-fuses in line with one side of each battery (3A fuse). This would give an extra layer of protection.

I was also having a ton of trouble with my printer these past few months. Bad adhesion, lifting corners bed not staying level. Replacing my heat bed with a metal bed has seemed to help. So I had to add ‘pads’ to the corners to prevents lifting.

The case take a long time to print, Top under 4 hrs, Bottom about 4.5 hrs. So if the corners come up half-way thru if can make you pull your hair out.

remixed_from.title: Externally Accessable Y axis belt tensioner for Taz 3-5 Printers

title: Taz 6 style Externally Accessable Y axis belt tensioner

description.text:
This project is an externally accessable M4 bolt driven Y axis belt tensioner for the Taz 6 series printer. Co designed by Kevin Davis

It will not work with any other Taz. For older Taz, or to see the general idea of how this works, check out the Taz 1-5 Variant here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1656341

Basically you will need 1 m4 bolt , 1 m4 washer and M4 nyloc nut, 2 M3 heat set inserts, 3 1/4" smooth threaded spacers (probably the 1 inch long ones), 6 6-32 1/2" long bolts to fit those spacers, 5 6-32 Washers, and the stock idler hardware from your Taz. You will also potentially want 4 long-ish M3 metric bolts and nuts to temporarily bolt the drill guide in place and an at least 4mm drill bit.

One spacer gets bolted to the middle of the base, with the bolt head recessed. so as to not hit the mounting plate. The other two replace 2 of the stock M3 bolts and heat set inserts.

Instructions:

  1. on the Idler mounting plate stripped of hardware, temporarily bolt the drill guide to the outside of the plate using M3 bolts and nuts and drill an at least 4mm dia hole (as long as an m4 bolt can pass through here you are ok). remove the guide and clean up the hole.
  2. Use the M4 bolt and washer to pull the nyloc m4 nut into the new tensioner nut socket. then remove the bolt.
  3. Assemble the idler pulley hardware.
  4. insert the 2 heat set inserts into the baseplate
  5. Bolt one of the 1/4" threaded spacers to the center-ish hole using one of the 6-32 bolts in the recess (after cleaning the hole)
  6. bolt the base plate to the idler mount plate using 2 of the stock m3 bolts and washers in the heat set insert holes, and 2 of the 6-32 bolts and washers and nylon spacers in the other two holes.
  7. Put the tensioner on the spacers, adjust for fit as needed.
  8. thread the M4 bolt and washer from outside the plate into the tensioner.
  9. Assemble the belt as usual, then use the M4 bolt to add tension
  10. Put three 6-32 bolts and washers in the other end of the threaded spacers. In the event the M4 bolt ever did break for some reason, those washers would prevent the tensioner from flying forward into the machine guts.

title: Tripod Thread Adapter for Xenz' "Webcam mount for Wanhao Di3 / Monoprice Maker Select v2.1"
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Hi all!

This is a simple adapter I made to allow for webcams with a standard tripod mount to be used with Xenz' "Webcam mount for Wanhao Di3 / Monoprice Maker Select v2.1". It was made by converting the Webcam Mount and Kahuna's "Tripod Thumb Screw" into meshes in FreeCAD, then performing a boolean union operation after refining the geometry.

Someone with more knowledge of modeling software would likely be able to make a more elegant solution, but I wanted to provide this, as it has worked well for my Logitech C615 Webcam, after some initial trial/error on the print settings.

To avoid prints that won't work with your webcam, or having the screw section break off inside your webcam's tripod mount, please use the tested settings outlined below.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

100%, Supports 10%

Notes:

The threaded screw from Kahuna's model is very weak to torsional force, due to size. Prints were attempted with different layer heights, infill %, orientation, wall thickness, and top/bottom thickness, which all failed due to the screw section breaking off from the base. To avoid headaches, please use the following settings:

Wall Thickness: 0.4mm or lower (higher will create drag on the screw section and cause it to break)

Top/Bottom Thickness: 0.4mm or lower (higher is not necessary, as we are printing at 100% infill to keep the screw section strong)

Infill: 100% (lower results in a weak screw that can break off inside the tripod mount)

Supports: Touching Buildplate

Support Infill Percentage: 10%

Alignment: Ball Cup side Down (eliminates risk of damaging screw section while removing supports)

Rafts/Brim/Skirt: Brim or Raft (supports may lift off build plate otherwise)

The tripod mount's screw section may be a little long for some webcams' threaded inserts, but it's thin, so if you like, you may trim it with some nippers or scissors after the print is done, or kill the print around half-way through the screw section. As always, if using tools to modify a part post-printing, please do so with care, and at your own risk.

That said, the settings mentioned above worked great for me when sliced via Cura 3.0, and using Monoprice PLA.

description.text:
I'm very fond of this extruder design so I decided to make some improvements. The original design is capable of pushing filament with great force albeit this requires the stepper to be driven with high current. Increased current means that the motor heats up and the heat is dissipating through all parts of the motor, including the axle and MK8 wheel which eventually will make the filament softer and deform causing feeding failure.

With the adding of the coling duct and the rear fan mount the motor will remain at room temperature or slightly above. The 40x40 mm fan should be oriented so that it sucks air out of the duct through the geels on each side of the duct.

I also included a standoff mount.

The original part is found here and is made by 50koruny.

The missing parts for the extruder front is the same as the original.

Design files for Fusion 360 is included

comments.text: I suppose you print at 300mm/s  3mm filament to need such a big forced air cooled extruder ?
comments.author: MKSA

comments.text: No, not at all. I print at moderate speeds and with 1,75 mm filament. I have, however, had issues with skipping extruder motors and heating up of the filament causing deformation and feed failure when pushing ABS at relatively low temperatures. Those days are gone now. The duct are made long to accomodate longer motors if needed.
comments.author: MKSA

comments.text:
So there is no need for such a heavy, complex to make extruder.
A Nema 17 has no problem, provided its current is correctly set, driving a 9mm hobbed gear with enough force to push 1.75 OD filament at the correct hot end T°.
As for Bowden, no justification to use it today. Plenty of issues and takes more force to drive the filament through the tube.A light direct extruder will work better or for Delta a flexible drive.
comments.author: Captain_sq

comments.text: Maybe so, all my printers are Bowden types and this extruder works perfectly for me. I'm however, going to make a Wade extruder with a very small stepper and a planetary gear when I can find the time.
